WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.600
Hi. I'm Jeff Alderson. I'm the Town Moderator in the Town of Natick, and I'm going to explain

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:13.480
how Town Meeting works through two real votes that happened right here in Natick.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:17.460
In Massachusetts, many towns have what's called Town Meeting.

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:20.280
It's like a student council for the whole town.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:25.680
Elected members vote on big things, like money, rules, and projects.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:35.080
Any resident in the town can come and speak at Town Meeting, but only elected members can vote.

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:40.440
My job, the moderator, that's me in Natick, is to make sure that things are fair,

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:45.040
that everyone gets a turn to speak, and I'm the one that gets to call out

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:49.600
what the actual vote count was, how many people were for or against a motion.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:01:00.680
You don't take sides as a moderator. You're there to act like a referee and make sure that everyone has time to speak their mind about the topic at hand.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:06.080
Two things happened in Natick recently. One, we debated whether or not the town should

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:11.920
phase out the use of gas leaf blowers.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:16.640
And the second was whether or not we shouldn't build any more artificial turf fields on school grounds.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:22.560
Both of these are real topics that people care a lot about.

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:29.000
So for that first question, there was a group in town called EcoNatick that wanted to phase out gas leaf blowers. Why?

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:35.080
Well, they're loud. They pollute the air. They might be able to make people sick.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:41.160
People wanted to switch to electric blowers, or just use a rake.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:45.680
Now, some people agreed with that. It was better for our health and the planet.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:51.240
And then some people disagreed. Electric blowers aren't strong enough yet for the big jobs,

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:55.240
and the new equipment and that new technology, it costs a lot of money.

00:01:55.240 --> 00:02:02.040
Both sides made really good points. And at Town Meeting, everyone listened to what they had to say.

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:09.300
But when it came time to vote, it was 79 yes, 27 no, and one abstain.

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:15.160
An abstain is just basically saying that that person didn't really want to vote on that issue.

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:21.160
The yes vote in this case meant that this was going to be sent to a study committee to learn about the topic more.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:27.000
No ban on gas leaf blowers just yet, just more studying.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.320
Now let's talk about the second question.

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:38.280
Some residents in town asked for a three-year pause on building new turf fields. In town, we call that a moratorium.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:47.320
They really didn't want to have new plastic turf fields because they were worried about player health and students and the environment.

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:56.080
While other people said that they needed more fields for kids to play on, and they didn't really care what type of turf or grass it was.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:02.720
One side said that microplastics, little bits of plastics and forever chemicals in the turf field, could be dangerous.

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:09.120
The fields get really hot too. The other side on the issue said that turf fields can be used way more than grass fields.

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:18.280
That gives students more time to play. And we don't have enough fields today for all the kids who do want to play in their own sports.

00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:23.280
The outcome of this vote was 74 yes, 28 no, and three abstain.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:28.880
In this case, the yes vote meant that the town agreed to the three-year pause.

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:35.000
No new artificial turf fields are going to be built in Natick for three years while the town studies the issue.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:42.920
Existing fields that already were there and may have already been made out of turf, they're fine. They can be maintained and they will stay.

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.360
So, what do we learn from these two examples?

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.320
Anyone can speak up.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:50.800
You don't have to be a leader or elected.

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:55.480
If you care about something, you can share your idea and discuss it.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:04:02.640
Debating also helps. Hearing different sides of an issue makes us think harder and make better choices.

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:09.960
And every vote counts. Each person that's elected to Town Meeting gets one vote and every vote matters.

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:11.160
And that's democracy.
